"}],["code",{"code":"keytool -genkey -v -keystore ~/key.jks -keyalg RSA -keysize 2048 -validity 10000 -alias key"}]],"markups":[["a",["href","http://talkdimsum.com/"]],["a",["href","https://flutter.dev/docs/deployment/android"]]],"sections":[[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"After settling on Flutter for Android development (abandoning Java, Kotlin, and React Native on the way), I'm pretty happy with it, but last year when I tried to upload a build of "],[0,[0],1,"Talk Dim Sum"],[0,[],0," to Google Play, I couldn't figure out how to get GP to accept my uploads."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"I gave it another try today, and after a series of missteps while follwing the "],[0,[1],1,"official doc"],[0,[],0,", succeeded. The first mistake I made was not noticing that I needed to change signingConfigs.debug to signingConfigs.release in build.gradle"]]],[10,0],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"I figured that out after a few consecutive complaints from Google Play that I was uploading a signed debug build."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"After that, my appbundle builds generated error messages that the keystore was not in the correct format.  Turns out I needed to add append -storetype JKS to this keytool invocation on my Mac (they do include it in the Windows sample)"]]],[10,1],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"That parameter is included in the Windows sample invocation, and alluded to in the follow-on note."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"From then on, all my problems were on the Google Play end."]]]],"ghostVersion":"4.0"}

